 {"id":"rust_proxy-wn9","title":"Update daemon to integrate file watching","description":"## Scope

Integrate the file watcher into the daemon's main loop so config changes are automatically detected and applied.

## Rationale

This ties together all the pieces: file watcher detects changes, ConfigHolder performs reload, and the daemon reacts appropriately. This is the integration point that makes hot reload actually work end-to-end.

## Implementation Details

### Daemon Main Loop Integration

```rust
pub async fn run_daemon() -> Result<()> {
    let config = AppConfig::load()?;
    let config_path = config_path()?;
    let config_holder = Arc::new(ConfigHolder::new(config.clone(), config_path.clone()));

    // Start file watcher
    let watcher = ConfigWatcher::new(&config_path)?;

    // Setup SIGHUP handler
    setup_signal_handlers(config_holder.clone()).await;

    // Spawn file watch task
    let watcher_config = config_holder.clone();
    tokio::spawn(async move {
        let mut interval = tokio::time::interval(Duration::from_secs(2));
        loop {
            interval.tick().await;
            if watcher.poll().is_some() {
                tracing::debug!("Config file change detected");
                if let Err(e) = watcher_config.reload().await {
                    tracing::error!(error = %e, "Auto-reload failed");
                }
            }
        }
    });

    // ... rest of daemon (listener, health checks, etc.)
}
```

### Propagating Config Changes

Components that need fresh config should either:
1. Call `config_holder.get()` on each use (simple, slightly more overhead)
2. Subscribe to change notifications and cache (more complex, better for hot paths)

For the proxy handler (called per-connection):
```rust
async fn handle_connection(
    stream: TcpStream,
    config_holder: Arc<ConfigHolder>,
    // ...
) {
    let config = config_holder.get().await;
    // Use config for this connection
}
```

For the health check loop (long-running):
```rust
async fn health_check_loop(
    config_holder: Arc<ConfigHolder>,
    // ...
) {
    let mut change_rx = config_holder.subscribe();

    loop {
        tokio::select! {
            _ = ticker.tick() => {
                let config = config_holder.get().await;
                run_health_checks(&config, &state).await;
            }
            Ok(diff) = change_rx.recv() => {
                if !diff.settings_changed.is_empty() {
                    // Settings changed, may need to adjust interval
                    tracing::info!("Health check settings updated");
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Error Recovery

If the file watcher fails (e.g., filesystem unmounted):
- Log error but don't crash
- SIGHUP still works as manual fallback
- Attempt to re-establish watcher periodically

